#Simulate sample mean and sd

Heres an old function:

sim_mean_sd = function(n_obs, mu = 5 , sigma = 1) {
  x_vec = rnorm(n = n_obs, mean = mu, sd= sigma)
  tibble(
    mean = mean(x_vec),
    sd = sd(x_vec)
  )
}

Lets run it:

sim_mean_sd(n_obs = 30)
## # A tibble: 1  2
##    mean    sd
##   <dbl> <dbl>
## 1  4.96 0.963

Lets iterate to see how this works UNDER REPEATED SAMPLING!!!

output = vector("list", length = 100)

for(i in 1:100){
  
  output[[i]] = sim_mean_sd(n_obs = 30)
  
}

sim_results =
  bind_rows(output)

use a map function

sim_results_df =
  expand_grid(
    sample_size = c(30, 60, 120, 240),
    iter = 1:1000
  ) %>%
  mutate(estimate_df = map(sample_size, sim_mean_sd)) %>%
  unnest(estimate_df)

sim_results_df %>%
  mutate(
    sample_size = str_c("n =", sample_size),
    sample_size = fct_inorder(sample_size)
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = sample_size, y = mean)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

Try binomal distribution now

sim_mean_sd = function(n_obs, true_p = 0.9) {
  x_vec = rbinom(n = n_obs, size = 1, prob = true_p)
  tibble(
    mean = mean(x_vec),
    sd = sd(x_vec)
  )
}

sim_results_df =
  expand_grid(
    sample_size = c(30, 60, 120, 240),
    iter = 1:1000
  ) %>%
  mutate(estimate_df = map(sample_size, sim_mean_sd)) %>%
  unnest(estimate_df)

sim_results_df %>%
  mutate(
    sample_size = str_c("n =", sample_size),
    sample_size = fct_inorder(sample_size)
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = sample_size, y = mean)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

Regression (SLR)

Goal is to write a function that simulates data and then fits a regression, then repeat to look at distribution of estimated coefficients

beta_0 = 2
beta_1 = 3

sim_data = 
  tibble(
    x = rnorm(n = 30, mean = 1, sd = 1),
    y = beta_0 + beta_1 * x + rnorm(30, mean = 0, sd = 1)
  )

ls_fit = lm(y ~ x, data = sim_data) #least squares fit

sim_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y =y)) + 
  geom_point()

Lets wrap this into a function

sim_slr = function(n_obs, beta_0 = 2, beta_1 = 3) {
  
  sim_data = tibble(
    x = rnorm(n = n_obs, mean = 1, sd = 1), 
    y = beta_0 + beta_1 * x + rnorm(n_obs, mean = 0, sd = 1)
  )
  
  ls_fit = lm(y ~ x, data = sim_data)
  
  tibble(
    beta0_hat = coef(ls_fit)[1],
    beta1_hat = coef(ls_fit)[2]
  )
}

sim_slr(n_obs = 30)
## # A tibble: 1  2
##   beta0_hat beta1_hat
##       <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1      1.81      3.00

run this a whole bunch of times

output = vector("list", length = 100)

for(i in 1:100){
  
  output[[i]] = sim_slr(n_obs = 30)
  
}
sim_results_df = 
  expand_grid(
    sample_size = 30,
    iter = 1:1000
  ) %>%
  mutate(estimate_df = map(sample_size, sim_slr)) %>%
  unnest(estimate_df)
